Before the roster, three design rules that matter more than any individual bot:

The panel's job is **coverage, not realism** — you want every corner of the strategy space, and the corner people forget is the *adaptive* one (bots that punish your aggression). That's the corner that keeps your reactive dial honest. Weight the population like the real qualifier field: mostly noobs, a solid block of adaptive punishers, a few balanced bots, one neural net, CFR optional. And don't hand-code eight noobs — write **one parametric naive bot** with knobs (vpip, pfr, aggression, fold-to-bet, call-down, bluff-freq) and sample its parameter space, so you get dense cheap coverage and can hold out whole regions for validation.Now the roster, by your five categories. For each I'll give the behavior, how to build it inside the sandbox, and — the part that matters — *which property of your own bot it stresses*.

**Noob field — build first, weight heaviest (~60% of the panel).** This is the real qualifier's long tail. Implement as one parametric rule-based bot, then pin a few fixed extremes:
- *Nit / scared-money*: opens only premiums, folds to any postflop aggression. Tests value extraction — this is your tight_heavy target and the bot your reactive dial must beat by stealing and barreling wider.
- *Calling station*: calls any bet with any pair or draw, almost never folds or raises. Tests that your dial correctly *stops* bluffing against stickiness (your `_AF_NEVER_BLUFF` instinct, applied as a continuous fold-to-bet read).
- *Maniac / spew*: jams and raises constantly, bluffs far too much. Tests that your TAG calls down light enough — v4.1 folds a lot to aggression, and over-folding to a maniac is a real leak.
- *Random-legal*: uniform over legal actions. Tests classifier robustness to noise and that you don't lose to a coinflip opponent.
- *Loose-passive limper* and *min-better*: cover the "plays too many hands but never aggresses" and "fixed-size / sizing-tell" gaps cheaply.

The factory itself (knobs sampled across ranges) gives you a *continuum* between these, which is what stops you overfitting to any one hand-coded noob.

**GTO-inspired — the "don't bleed against good players" check (~15%).** Two bots:
- *PreflopGTO + balanced postflop*: reuse the position-aware charts you're building for your own GTO preflop extension, plus a fixed-frequency c-bet (~⅓ range) and pot-odds calls with a set bluff:value ratio, mixed via a spot-seeded RNG. Tests that your reactive dial ramps **λ → 0** against a balanced opponent — if it keeps deviating and bleeding here, your gate is mis-calibrated.
- *MDF defender*: postflop, defends at exactly minimum-defense-frequency for each bet size you use (`fold = b/(p+b)`, defends the rest weighted toward stronger hands). This is the single most diagnostic bot in the whole panel: if your aggression dial still profits against a *perfect* defender, your edge is real aggression that beats everyone; if it only profits against the nit/station, your edge is purely "they fold too much" — which is fine to know, but tells you it's an exploit, not a fundamental.

**Exploiters / adaptive — the safety-critical punishers (~20%).** These adapt to *you*, and they're the corner that catches a reckless dial:
- *Counter-exploiter (trap)*: tracks your c-bet/barrel frequency; plays straightforwardly until it detects you're attacking, then switches to check-raising and floating to punish. It directly attacks your reactive layer — if your dial over-commits to a fold read, this bot induces it and snaps back. Tests whether your dial has a "back off when punished" feedback rather than ramping blindly.
- *Level-2 sizing-reader*: estimates your range from your bet size and calls/raises accordingly. This one will find a *real* leak in v4.1 — your `_postflop_by_equity` bets 0.5-pot as its only bluff size but 0.7–0.9-pot for value, a transparent tell. If this bot beats you, you need to randomize or merge your sizings.
- *Gear-shifter*: changes style every K hands (tight → loose → aggro). Tests your stats machinery's hidden assumption that opponents are *stationary* — your `PLAYER_STATS` accumulate forever, so a bot that shifts will leave you reading a stale average. May motivate a decay/windowed stat.

**Mini neural-netter — the classifier false-positive check (~5%).** A small MLP (numpy forward pass, or an `sklearn` `MLPClassifier`/logistic policy) trained *offline* — behavioral-clone it from your GTO bot's or heuristic bots' decision logs, so it plays smooth, decent, non-archetypal poker. Its value isn't that it's strong; it's that it has *no clean type*. The test: a smooth opponent should keep your classifier confidence **low**, so your dial stays off. If your dial fires on a net that merely happens to fold a bit, you've found a false-positive that would misfire against real sophisticated opponents too.

**CFR — optional, and honestly the lowest panel priority.** A preflop-CFR blueprint (or a toy single-street postflop solve, shipped as a lookup) is your hardest, least-exploitable sparring partner. But be deliberate here: the GTO charts + MDF defender already cover the "can I survive a near-equilibrium opponent" role at a fraction of the effort, so a full CFR *opponent* is mostly redundant for the panel. Spend CFR effort on **your own** blueprint direction instead. If you do want one, preflop-only is the cheapest version that teaches you anything.

Two last things. Hold out a **validation split** — tune your dial against half the factory samples plus one trap config, and validate on factory samples and a trap config you never touched; anything that helps train-but-not-validate is overfit, reject it. And seed every bot so matches are reproducible for your CRN pairing.

The two highest-leverage pieces to build first are the **parametric naive factory** (gives you the whole noob continuum in one file) and the **counter-exploiter trap** (the one bot that validates your dial is safe). Want me to write either of those as starter `decide()` code against your engine's state schema?
